PART 1 — DOCUMENT CONTROL AND OWNERSHIP
1. Document Purpose, Ownership, and Change Control
1.1 Purpose
This specification defines the plenor.ai website/application to be built and operated. It is the authoritative product specification for the current phase.

1.2 Scope of this specification
This specification defines:
•	product goals and priorities
•	users, jobs to be done, capabilities, features, and priorities
•	navigation and information architecture
•	content model
•	page and view requirements
•	inquiry and lead-capture flows
•	CMS management behavior
•	site configuration governance
•	responsive application requirements
•	accessibility requirements
•	search, metadata, and URL governance
•	technical setup expectations
•	site operations
•	quality requirements and acceptance criteria
•	derived LLM build prompt requirements

Dependent Instruments
This specification is accompanied by a required dependent instrument family: the Site Configuration Standard and the Site Configuration Record. The Site Configuration Standard defines the governed configuration model, rules, validation logic, and completion criteria for the configuration categories established in §8.6. The Site Configuration Record defines the active current-phase values that instantiate that model for the plenor.ai site. Both instruments must be satisfied. Both are subordinate to this specification in governance terms but authoritative within their own declared scopes. Neither overrides the other within its own domain.

1.3 Ownership
The document owner is the plenor.ai product/site owner or delegated website owner.

1.4 Intended use
This specification is intended to guide:
•	website design
•	web application implementation
•	CMS configuration
•	content modeling
•	LLM-assisted code generation
•	acceptance review

1.5 Prohibited use
This specification must not be treated as:
•	a generic startup website template
•	a substitute for CMS platform documentation
•	permission to introduce unsupported or out-of-scope features
•	permission to silently inherit patterns from the current live site if they contradict this specification

1.6 Change control
Changes to this specification must be made through controlled revision. Downstream implementation must not silently override specification content.

Changes to required dependent instruments of this specification, including the Site Configuration Standard and Site Configuration Record, are subject to the same change control discipline. A change to a dependent instrument that affects a requirement, constraint, or acceptance criterion governed by this specification must be treated as a governed change and must not be made without review against this specification.

1.7 Authority of downstream prompt
Any LLM build prompt derived from this specification is subordinate to this specification and may not expand or contradict it.

PART 2 — WEBSITE GOALS, PRODUCT REQUIREMENTS, AND OPERATING PRINCIPLES
2. Website Goals, Priorities, Constraints, and Operating Principles
2.1 Product framing
Plenor.ai is a CMS-operated, company-and-offer-centered, framework-demonstrating, lead-generating, responsive web application.

It is the public website for plenor.ai and also serves as the first concrete demonstration of the CMS-driven website approach plenor.ai intends to use.

2.2 Product goals
The product must:
•	explain what plenor.ai is clearly and credibly
•	explain the website/framework approach without requiring technical interpretation by visitors
•	present plenor.ai's offers, thinking, and differentiators in a structured way
•	enable routine content and design-management work through the CMS without developer dependence
•	support lead generation through inquiry and resource capture paths
•	remain usable and coherent across desktop, tablet, and mobile
•	provide a strong enough content and structure model that the site can later evolve without architectural rewrite
•	make site content understandable to both human visitors and search engines through clear information structure, descriptive metadata, and crawlable internal linking

2.3 Priority hierarchy
Priority hierarchy governs homepage emphasis, feature priority, navigation emphasis, implementation order, and what remains supporting rather than dominant. It must be treated as a genuine prioritization rule, not decorative language.

2.3.1 Primary — Company positioning and framework/service clarity
What plenor.ai is, what problem it solves, how the approach works, and how a prospective customer engages.

2.3.2 Secondary — Offer explanation and proof
Capabilities, service or solution areas, selected examples, implementation approach, and credibility-building content.

2.3.3 Tertiary — Insights and reusable knowledge
Articles, essays, guidance, resources, and framework-oriented explanatory content.

2.3.4 Supporting — Company background and contact paths
About, contact, FAQs, policy pages, and other supporting trust surfaces.

2.4 Constraints
The product must operate within these constraints:
•	routine content management must occur through the CMS
•	routine design and layout adjustments must occur through approved CMS controls where supported
•	custom development should be avoided when the CMS/platform default behavior is sufficient
•	theme control is curated for the current phase
•	the current phase is for plenor.ai only and does not need to expose multi-site administration
•	the site must not depend on placeholder production content such as generic contact data, generic branding labels, or uncustomized policy identity text
•	generic framework capability may be implied by structure and behavior, but the site is not required to expose a separate platform product area in the current phase unless explicitly enabled
•	all production pages must use accurate company identity, contact information, and policy ownership details
•	the production site must be served over HTTPS

2.5 Operating principles
The product must follow these operating principles:
•	content is created once and reused across approved locations
•	company positioning and offer clarity take precedence over decorative marketing language
•	CMS-managed behavior comes first; platform default behavior is the fallback when needed
•	shared components remain structurally stable
•	flexible content control exists only within approved boundaries
•	every user-facing feature must trace to a defined user need and site purpose
•	the website must be credible as both a company site and a demonstration of disciplined CMS-driven implementation
•	accessibility is a first-class product requirement, not a later-stage enhancement
•	headings, labels, link text, and calls to action must be descriptive and understandable out of context
•	form interactions must minimize user error and provide clear recovery paths

3. Users, Jobs to Be Done, Capabilities, Features, and Priorities
3.1 Governing traceability chain
All user-facing and CMS-facing features must be justified through this chain:

User → Job to Be Done → Capability → Feature → Page/View or CMS Surface → Priority

A feature may not be introduced unless it can be traced through this chain.

3.2 Priority levels
•	P1 — mandatory for MVP
•	P2 — important but not blocking MVP
•	P3 — optional or later-phase

3.2A Priority application rule
•	P1 — mandatory for MVP and required to satisfy primary users or primary operational needs
•	P2 — important for usability, visibility, credibility, or manageability, but not blocking MVP
•	P3 — optional or future-phase

A page, view, content type, or workflow element may not be treated as P1 unless it directly supports a P1 capability.

3.3 User set
3.3.1 Website Admin / Owner
A CMS/editorial role with full control over site content, publishing, configuration, approved visual settings, and reusable content selection.

3.3.2 Contributor / Editor
A CMS/editorial role with limited content contribution rights and controlled publishing authority.

3.3.3 Prospective Customer / Buyer
A public user seeking to understand what plenor.ai offers, whether it is relevant, and how to engage.

3.3.4 Evaluator / Researching Visitor
A public user comparing options, assessing credibility, and reviewing framework or method depth before engaging.

3.3.5 Partner / Collaborator
A public user seeking to understand plenor.ai's approach, positioning, and collaboration fit.

3.3.6 General Reader
A public user consuming explanatory, educational, or insight-oriented content without immediate buying intent.

